issue.title: solfuzzer terminates with a crash on inputs containing invalid UTF-8 (mild obstacle to fuzzing)
issue.body:
Given any .sol input from standard input that contains invalid UTF-8 (which will frequently be produced by byte-mutating fuzzers like AFL), solfuzzer fails like this:

```
Testing compiler with optimizer.
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'nlohmann::json_abi_v3_11_3::detail::type_error'
  what():  [json.exception.type_error.316] invalid UTF-8 byte at index 35: 0x80
Aborted
```

This looks like a crash to the fuzzer, so produces lots of spurious crashes and an annoying burden for triage.  The solc executable does not crash on such inputs, as far as I can see.  This isn't a major problem, fuzzing still works, but it definitely imposes a cost (of 9 million executions of solfuzzer in one fuzzing run, over 3 million have been crashes due to this UTF-8 issue, and with a larger starting corpus especially the crash set is composed of a huge number of ways to reach this uninteresting non-bug crash).

This is on the latest solc/solidity (0.8.24 github main branch)

## Steps to Reproduce

Just run solfuzzer on an input like:

```
contract test {
    f\200^@ction g() pu\203lic { f(); }
}
```

`build/test/tools/solfuzzer < crash.sol`

# Fix QueryJob total_rows attribute error ## Summary This PR fixes a critical `AttributeError` that occurs when the BigQuery API returns a `QueryJob` object without the `total_rows` attribute. The error `'QueryJob' object has no attribute 'total_rows'` was causing the application to crash when users asked questions like "how many republicans are there". **Root Cause:** The BigQuery `QueryJob` object doesn't always populate the `total_rows` attribute, particularly for certain query types (like COUNT queries) or under specific conditions. The code was attempting to access this attribute directly, causing an AttributeError. **Fix:** Changed from direct attribute access `query_job.total_rows` to safe access using `getattr(query_job, 'total_rows', None)`, which returns None if the attribute doesn't exist rather than raising an exception. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Critical**: Test end-to-end with actual BigQuery queries that return results (not just permission errors) to verify the fix works and doesn't break normal functionality - [ ] **High**: Verify truncation detection still works correctly when `total_rows` is available vs when it's None - [ ] **Medium**: Test various query types (SELECT, COUNT, aggregations, complex queries) to ensure consistent behavior across different BigQuery response patterns **Recommended Test Plan:** 1.
